<collectionCode id="76B77A98A523FFFEFB79FC9EFA9E737B" box="[1270,1345,806,832]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15722" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15722" name="Santa Barbara Botanic Garden" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" type="Herbarium">SBBG</collectionCode>
49613!
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1019E25DA523FFFEFF32FCF3FD597406" blockId="11.[136,1452,230,1373]" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">
We find 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFE97FCF2FE3A735F" authorityName=", Johnston" authorityYear="1928" box="[280,485,842,868]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pondii">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFE97FCF2FE3A735F" box="[280,485,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">Cryptantha pondii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be quite distinctive from other taxa in several features. It has linear bracts sporadically subtending peduncle bases of the cymules as well as flowers (
<figureCitation id="889DFED8A523FFFEFCB2FCD6FC0973B2" box="[829,982,878,905]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[136,229,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[245,1343,196,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-19@12.[237,1350,190,1807]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Cryptantha pondii. A. Close-up of single plant of presumed lectotype specimen (US41006), confirmed by Johnston (1928) as being correctly identified. Note linear, pustulate leaves and bracts at base of cymules. B,C. Images from Gentry 8684, 13 March 1949 (HCIB21969). B. Four nutlets removed from fruit, showing smooth surface and slight size heteromorphism. C. Close-up of cymules, showing linear bracts and relatively large corollas. D–F. Images from Philbrick B74-84, 25 March 1974 (SBBG49613). D. Fruit with four, smooth nutlets removed. Note finely hirsute calyx marginal region with ascending trichomes, as well as hispid calyx midrib of stouter trichomes. E. Close-up of four nutlets attached to gynobase. Note slight heteromorphism in size and slight extension of style tip/stigma from nutlet apices. F. Cymules, showing appressed-strigose vestiture of axes, scattered linear flower bracts, and relatively large corolla." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426148/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">Fig. 6A, C, F</figureCitation>
). The calyces are somewhat finely hirsute with ascending trichomes, described as “silky-hirsute” by 
<bibRefCitation id="74379FACA523FFFEFC94FC2AFC227397" author="Johnston, I. M." box="[795,1021,914,940]" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" pagination="73 - 83" refId="ref13085" refString="Johnston, I. M. (1928) Studies in the Boraginaceae - VII. 2. Notes on various Boraginoideae. Contributions from the Gray Herbarium of Harvard University 81: 73 - 83." type="journal article" year="1928">Johnston (1928: 74)</bibRefCitation>
in addition to hispid along the midrib (
<figureCitation id="889DFED8A523FFFEFF1FFC0EFED873EA" box="[144,263,950,977]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[136,229,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[245,1343,196,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-19@12.[237,1350,190,1807]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Cryptantha pondii. A. Close-up of single plant of presumed lectotype specimen (US41006), confirmed by Johnston (1928) as being correctly identified. Note linear, pustulate leaves and bracts at base of cymules. B,C. Images from Gentry 8684, 13 March 1949 (HCIB21969). B. Four nutlets removed from fruit, showing smooth surface and slight size heteromorphism. C. Close-up of cymules, showing linear bracts and relatively large corollas. D–F. Images from Philbrick B74-84, 25 March 1974 (SBBG49613). D. Fruit with four, smooth nutlets removed. Note finely hirsute calyx marginal region with ascending trichomes, as well as hispid calyx midrib of stouter trichomes. E. Close-up of four nutlets attached to gynobase. Note slight heteromorphism in size and slight extension of style tip/stigma from nutlet apices. F. Cymules, showing appressed-strigose vestiture of axes, scattered linear flower bracts, and relatively large corolla." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426148/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">Fig. 6D, F</figureCitation>
). And, we confirm the observations of 
<bibRefCitation id="74379FACA523FFFEFD39FC0EFC4A73EB" author="Johnston, I. M." box="[694,917,950,976]" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" pagination="73 - 83" refId="ref13085" refString="Johnston, I. M. (1928) Studies in the Boraginaceae - VII. 2. Notes on various Boraginoideae. Contributions from the Gray Herbarium of Harvard University 81: 73 - 83." type="journal article" year="1928">Johnston (1928: 74)</bibRefCitation>
that the corollas are relatively large (
<figureCitation id="889DFED8A523FFFEFABDFC0EFA7873EA" box="[1330,1447,950,977]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[136,229,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[245,1343,196,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-19@12.[237,1350,190,1807]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Cryptantha pondii. A. Close-up of single plant of presumed lectotype specimen (US41006), confirmed by Johnston (1928) as being correctly identified. Note linear, pustulate leaves and bracts at base of cymules. B,C. Images from Gentry 8684, 13 March 1949 (HCIB21969). B. Four nutlets removed from fruit, showing smooth surface and slight size heteromorphism. C. Close-up of cymules, showing linear bracts and relatively large corollas. D–F. Images from Philbrick B74-84, 25 March 1974 (SBBG49613). D. Fruit with four, smooth nutlets removed. Note finely hirsute calyx marginal region with ascending trichomes, as well as hispid calyx midrib of stouter trichomes. E. Close-up of four nutlets attached to gynobase. Note slight heteromorphism in size and slight extension of style tip/stigma from nutlet apices. F. Cymules, showing appressed-strigose vestiture of axes, scattered linear flower bracts, and relatively large corolla." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426148/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">Fig. 6C, F</figureCitation>
; described as 
<quantity id="D75E4FB8A523FFFEFE97FC62FEAA73CE" box="[280,373,986,1013]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3 mm</quantity>
broad by him, which we confirm here) and that there are four nutlets per fruit, these smooth and shiny and heteromorphic by size, with the odd nutlet axial (closest to the inflorescence axis) slightly larger than the other three consimilar nutlets (
<figureCitation id="889DFED8A523FFFEFE50FB9AFDA67406" box="[479,633,1058,1085]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[136,229,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[245,1343,196,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-19@12.[237,1350,190,1807]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Cryptantha pondii. A. Close-up of single plant of presumed lectotype specimen (US41006), confirmed by Johnston (1928) as being correctly identified. Note linear, pustulate leaves and bracts at base of cymules. B,C. Images from Gentry 8684, 13 March 1949 (HCIB21969). B. Four nutlets removed from fruit, showing smooth surface and slight size heteromorphism. C. Close-up of cymules, showing linear bracts and relatively large corollas. D–F. Images from Philbrick B74-84, 25 March 1974 (SBBG49613). D. Fruit with four, smooth nutlets removed. Note finely hirsute calyx marginal region with ascending trichomes, as well as hispid calyx midrib of stouter trichomes. E. Close-up of four nutlets attached to gynobase. Note slight heteromorphism in size and slight extension of style tip/stigma from nutlet apices. F. Cymules, showing appressed-strigose vestiture of axes, scattered linear flower bracts, and relatively large corolla." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426148/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">Fig. 6B, D, E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1019E25DA523FFFEFF32FBFFFC2B7567" blockId="11.[136,1452,230,1373]" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">
We note that although 
<bibRefCitation id="74379FACA523FFFEFE45FBFEFD5C745B" author="Johnston, I. M." box="[458,643,1094,1120]" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" pagination="73 - 83" refId="ref13085" refString="Johnston, I. M. (1928) Studies in the Boraginaceae - VII. 2. Notes on various Boraginoideae. Contributions from the Gray Herbarium of Harvard University 81: 73 - 83." type="journal article" year="1928">Johnston (1928)</bibRefCitation>
described the nutlets of 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFC26FBFFFBC9745B" authorityName=", Johnston" authorityYear="1928" box="[937,1046,1094,1121]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pondii">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFC26FBFFFBC9745B" box="[937,1046,1094,1121]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. pondii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as “smooth or very obscurely and minutely tuberculate above the middle”, we did not observe the latter sculpturing; all nutlets we observed were smooth and shiny. In addition, we were unable to observe specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFC5CFB37FBA07493" authorityName="Greene" authorityYear="1892" box="[979,1151,1166,1193]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bartolomaei">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFC5CFB37FBA07493" box="[979,1151,1166,1193]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. bartolomaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which Johnston believed to be synonymous with 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFE12FB0BFDD774F7" authorityName=", Johnston" authorityYear="1928" box="[413,520,1202,1229]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pondii">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFE12FB0BFDD774F7" box="[413,520,1202,1229]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. pondii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In fact, the type of 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFD77FB0BFC7B74F7" authorityName="Greene" authorityYear="1892" box="[760,932,1202,1229]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bartolomaei">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFD77FB0BFC7B74F7" box="[760,932,1202,1229]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. bartolomaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
he believed was derived from the very same collection as that of 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFEFFFB6FFE0574CB" authorityName=", Johnston" authorityYear="1928" box="[368,474,1238,1265]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pondii">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFEFFFB6FFE0574CB" box="[368,474,1238,1265]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. pondii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Online images of 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFD3AFB6FFCBF74CB" authorityName="Greene" authorityYear="1892" box="[693,864,1238,1265]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bartolomaei">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFD3AFB6FFCBF74CB" box="[693,864,1238,1265]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. bartolomaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus id="CF1D5CFFA523FFFEFCFFFB6EFC0774CB" box="[880,984,1238,1264]" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">holotype</typeStatus>
: 
<accessionNumber id="0FF57FBEA523FFFEFC6BFB6EFBB574CB" box="[996,1130,1238,1264]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/NDG40169" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">
<collectionCode id="76B77A98A523FFFEFC6BFB6EFBFC74CB" box="[996,1059,1238,1264]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15196" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15196" name="University of Notre Dame" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" type="Herbarium">NDG</collectionCode>
40169
</accessionNumber>
; isotypes: 
<collectionCode id="76B77A98A523FFFEFB6DFB6EFAD574CB" box="[1250,1290,1238,1264]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15631" name="Harvard University - Gray Herbarium" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" type="Herbarium">GH</collectionCode>
00096299 and 
<collectionCode id="76B77A98A523FFFEFF07FB42FF6E752F" box="[136,177,1274,1300]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15631" name="Harvard University - Gray Herbarium" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" type="Herbarium">GH</collectionCode>
00096293, the last apparently a fragment from the 
<typeStatus id="CF1D5CFFA523FFFEFD77FB42FC83752E" box="[760,860,1274,1301]" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">holotype</typeStatus>
) do fit our concept of 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFBEEFB43FB14752F" authorityName=", Johnston" authorityYear="1928" box="[1121,1227,1274,1301]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pondii">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFBEEFB43FB14752F" box="[1121,1227,1274,1301]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. pondii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the type specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFEADFAA7FE137503" authorityName="Greene" authorityYear="1892" box="[290,460,1310,1337]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bartolomaei">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFEADFAA7FE137503" box="[290,460,1310,1337]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. bartolomaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
need to be examined and verified as equivalent to 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFB8AFAA7FBB17503" authorityName=", Johnston" authorityYear="1928" box="[1029,1134,1310,1337]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pondii">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFB8AFAA7FBB17503" box="[1029,1134,1310,1337]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. pondii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, something we plan to do in the future. Note that 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFEFEFAFBFE067567" authorityName=", Johnston" authorityYear="1928" box="[369,473,1346,1373]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pondii">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFEFEFAFBFE067567" box="[369,473,1346,1373]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C. pondii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has priority of publication over 
<taxonomicName id="D7A699DEA523FFFEFCCCFAFBFC2E7567" authorityName="Greene" authorityYear="1892" box="[835,1009,1346,1373]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="196" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bartolomaei">
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFCCCFAFBFC897566" box="[835,854,1347,1373]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFCEBFAFAFC2E7567" box="[868,1009,1346,1372]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">bartolomaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="22D23E4FA523FFFEFC7FFAFAFC2B7567" box="[1008,1012,1346,1372]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="196">.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
